<h1><img src="/pub/Graphics/Icons/construction_dead.gif" ALT="">
<a name="top">EFF &quot;Legislation - Old - by Sponsor Name(s)&quot; Archive</a></h1>

<H5># NOTE: This index is not yet complete.
<br>boucher_hr1757.eff - May 1993 letter from the EFF to Rep Boucher in
<br> enthusiastic support for H.R. 1757, his initiative to
<br> promote applications of high-performance computer
<br> networking for education, libraries, health care,
<br> access to government information, and the public at large
<br>boucher_hr1757_93.bill -
<br>boucher_hr1757_93_vote.count -
<br>boxer_s1589.bill - Senate's &quot;Driver's Privacy Protection Act of 1993
<br> introduced by Senator Boxer. The purpose of this title
<br> is to protect the personal privacy and safety of licensed
<br> drivers consistent with the legitimate needs of business
<br> and government
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626.bill - November 28 version of The Antitrust Reform
<br> Act of 1993 sponsored by Rep Brooks and Dingell
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626.changes - Summary of Original bills and Revisions to
<br> House Bills 3636 and 3626.
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626.mfj - January 1994 summary of the Antitrust reform
<br> Act of 1993 HR 3626 put together by the MFJ Task
<br> Force
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626.summary - EFF Analysis of Bill HR-3626 Antitrust
<br> Reform Act of 1993 Introduced by Reps. Brooks
<br> and Dingell...briefly...This bill would phase
<br> out the limitations placed on the Bell
<br> Companies under the modified consent decree
<br> that resulted in the antitrust agreement that
<br> broke up AT&amp;T in 1982 (the &quot;MFJ&quot; or
<br> &quot;Modification of Final Judgment&quot;). The MFJ
<br> currently precludes Bell Companies from
<br> providing long distance service and
<br> manufacturing telephone equipment
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626_cullen.testimony - Feb 1994 testimony of James
<br> Cullen before the house committe on
<br> the judiciary's economic and
<br> commercial law subcommittee regarding
<br> the Communications Reform Act of
<br> 1993.
<br>brooks_dingell_hr3626_hr3636_ecc-tfs.testimony - Feb 1994 testimony of
<br> Edward Horowitz (CEO of
<br> Viacom) before the house
<br> energy and commerce's
<br> telecommunications and
<br> finance subcommittee
<br> relating to interactive video
<br> systems
<br>brown_hr5199.bill - 
<br>brown_hr5199_bill.draft - 
<br>brown_hr5199_cover.letter - 
<br>brown_hr5199_draft_eff.comments - 
<br>cantwell_hr3627-hr3937_crypto.excerpt - Excerpt from hr 3937 relating to
<br> the effects of the bill on other acts.
<br>cantwell_hr3627-hr3937_intell_cmte.report - June 1994 report by Rep
<br> Glickman regarding the &quot;Omnibus
<br> Export Administration Act of1994.&quot;
<br>cantwell_hr3627.analysis - Packet of information on Cantwell's 1994 export
<br> control liberalization for information security and
<br> products bill including some introductory info,
<br> full text of the bill, and analysis of what the
<br> bill means, after the press release immediately
<br> below
<br>cantwell_hr3627.bill - Cantwell's 1994 export control liberalization for
<br> information security and products bill. The United
<br> States' export control system is broken. It was
<br> designed as a tool of the cold-war, to help fight 
<br> against enemies that no longer exist. The myriad of
<br> Federal agencies responsible for controlling the
<br> flow of exports from our country must have a new
<br> charter, recognizing today's realities
<br>cantwell_hr3627.summary - Representative Maria Cantwell's November 1993
<br> remarks to the House of Representatives when she
<br> introduced H.R. 3627, Legislation to Amend the
<br> Export Administration Act of 1979. Her synopsis of
<br> the bill appears at the end
<br>clinton_admin_s1822_amend.draft - This is a *draft* of the Clinton
<br> Administration's proposed new regulatory
<br> scheme for interactive broadband networks.
<br> 1994. It was intended as an amendment to
<br> S.1822, the Senate's telecom reform bill,
<br> but was rejected (as was the entire bill
<br> eventually.) Commonly referred to as &quot;the
<br> Title VII amendment&quot; (linked to file
<br> hollings_danforth_s1822_clinton_admin_
<br> amend.draft)
<br>cooper_91_hr3515_kapor.testimony - Testimony of Mitch Kapor of the EFF
<br> before the subcommittee on telecom and
<br> finance regarding telecom infrastructure
<br> legislation and proposals In October 1991
<br>cooper_hr3515.bill - Cooper's failed Telecommunications Act of 1991 (incl.
<br> some analysis by James Bryant).
<br>danforth_inouye_s1086.bill - Senator Danforth's June 1993 &quot;Telecommunications
<br> Infrastructure Act of 1993' which, though it did
<br> not even get out of the committee level, might be
<br> revised in the future.
<br>danforth_inouye_s1086.summary - summary of s1086 (telecom_infra_s1086.bill)
<br> by the EFF explaining that s1086 would
<br> eliminate the legal monopoly that local
<br> telephone companies have on local phone
<br> service, allow any communications provider to
<br> offer local phone service, and allow local
<br> telephone companies to compete fully in the
<br> cable television market
<br>danforth_inouye_s1086_kapor.testimony - Mitch Kapor's September 1993
<br> testimony before the senate
<br> subcommittee on communications
<br> regarding s1086
<br> (telecom_infra_s1086.bill)
<br>deconcini_s1854.bill - S. 1854 by Sen. Dennis DeConcini (D-AZ) Patent Term and
<br> Publication Reform Act of 1994 According to LegiSlate,
<br> the bill &quot;would concern patent simplification and
<br> specificially would first implement a 20-year patent
<br> term beginning from the application file date, as
<br> well as ensure the publication of all patent
<br> applications after 18 months. The change of the patent
<br> term would better enable the United States to compete
<br> with most other industrialized countries,which also
<br> feature 20-year patent terms.&quot;
<br>deconcini_warner_et-al_s1948.bill - full text of s1948 &quot;Counterintelligence
<br> and Security Enhancement Act of 1994&quot;
<br> which would mend the National Security Act
<br> of1947 to improve the counterintelligence
<br> and security posture of the United States
<br> intelligence community and to enhance the
<br> investigative authority of the Federal
<br> Bureau of Investigation
<br> incounterintelligence matters, and for
<br> other purposes. A dangerous bill!!!!
<br>exon_s1822.amend - Here is the July 1994 text of the Exon &quot;Communications
<br> Decency&quot; amendment to the Communications Act of 1994 (S.
<br> 1822) Included here is the amendment text, Sen. Exon's
<br> introductory speech, and an article placed in the Cong.
<br> Record to bolster his position.
<br>gejdenson_hr3937_94_amended.bill - Export Administration Act of 1994, after
<br> Cantwell's crypto export language 
<br> (orginally from bill HR3627) was stripped 
<br> from it and replaced with a call for a 
<br> study of crypto export. Shows many
<br> amendments.
<br>gejdenson_hr3937_94_bill.old - Export Administration Act of 1994, before
<br> Cantwell's crypto export language
<br> (orginally from bill HR3627) was added and
<br> subsequently stripped (and before many other
<br> amendments.)
<br>gore_hr656_91.bill -
<br>gore_s1067_89.bill -
<br>gore_s272_91.bill -
<br>gore_s272_cst-sts_030591.testimony -
<br>gore_s272_hr656_91.act -
<br>gore_s2937_92.bill -
<br>gore_s2937_92.summary -
<br>hollings_danforth_s1822.bill - Feb 3, 1994 version of the &quot;Communications
<br> Act of 1994&quot; s1822 to...briefly...foster the
<br> further development of the Nation's
<br> telecommunications infrastructure and
<br> protection of the public interest, and for
<br> other purposes
<br>hollings_danforth_s1822_clinton_admin_amend.draft - (link to file clinton_
<br> admin_s1822_amend.draft)
<br>hollings_danforth_s1822_cullen.testimony - March 1994 testimony of James
<br> Cullen (president of Bell Atlantic)
<br> before the Senate Commerce
<br> Committee regarding s1822
<br> &quot;Communiations ACt of 1994&quot;
<br>hollings_danforth_s1822_exon.amend - Here is the July 1994 text of the
<br> Exon &quot;Communications Decency&quot;
<br> amendment to the Communications Act of
<br> 1994 (S. 1822) Included here is the
<br> amendment text, Sen. Exon's introductory
<br> speech, and an article placed in the
<br> Cong. Record to bolster his position.
<br>hollings_mitchell_s4.bill - This bill would grant the FBI broad powers to
<br> collect credit-record information on people,
<br> *without a warrant* it is called the &quot;National
<br> Competitiveness Act of 1993&quot; and its stated goal
<br> is to promote the industrial competitiveness and
<br> economic growth of the United States by
<br> strengthening and expanding the civilian
<br> technology programs of the Department of Commerce,
<br> amending the Stevenson-Wydler Technology
<br> Innovation Act of1980 to enhance the development
<br> and nationwide deployment of manufacturing
<br> technologies, and authorizing appropriations for
<br> the Technology Administration of the
<br> Department of Commerce, including the National
<br> Institute of Standards and Technology, and for
<br> other purposes
<br>inouye_nii_s2195.bill -
<br>kohl_s652_cnid_92.bill - s652 1992 To protect the privacy of
<br> telephone users by amending section 3121
<br> of title 18, United States Code
<br>lantos_hr3785.summary - Summary of Lantos' &quot;Video Game Rating Act of 1994&quot;
<br> A bill to &quot;provide for the establishment of the
<br> Interactive Entertainment Rating Comission, and for
<br> other purposes
<br>leahy_brown_s1782.bill - &quot;Electronic Freedom of Information Improvement
<br> Act of 1993&quot;. introduced by Leahy and Brown hoping to
<br> assure that Government agencies use new technology to
<br> enhance public access to information
<br>leahy_edwards_biden_s2375_hr4922.bill -
<br>leahy_edwards_biden_s2375_hr4922.readme -
<br>leahy_edwards_biden_s2375_hr4922_analysis.eff -
<br>leahy_edwards_biden_s2375_hr4922_passage_statement.eff -
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.amend - Amendment suggested by Senator Markey to hr 3636
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.analysis - March 1994 EFF summary of the introductory
<br> markup of hr 3636, &quot;The National
<br> Communications Competition and Information
<br> Infrastructure Act of 1994.&quot;
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.announce - announcement of Markey's debut of the&quot;National
<br> Communications Competition and Information
<br> Infrastructure Act of 1993.&quot; and a brief
<br> summary of the bill as well as praising by the
<br> EFF
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.bill - Amended version of Markey-Fields bill, HR
<br> 3636, after initial markup. This is NOT the final
<br> version. For further amendmentsto this
<br> post-initial-markup Markey-Fields bill HR 3636;
<br> see hr3636.amend. Even that is not the final
<br> version. More will follow when available
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.changes - Summary of Revisions to House Bills 3636
<br> and 3626 which are designed to provide more
<br> opportunity for competition in long-distance
<br> telephone, cable television, and cellular
<br> communication services. HR 3636 would allow
<br> cable and telephone companies to compete in
<br> each other's lines of business. HR 3626 is a
<br> major antitrust reform measure and would allow
<br> the regional Bell telephone operating
<br> companies, known as Baby Bells or RBOCs, to
<br> offer long-distance services
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.mfj - MFJ Task Force's Jan 1994 summary of hr3636 
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.old - November 1993 version of HR 3636
<br>markey_fields_hr3636.summary - EFF Position Statement on and Summary of
<br> Bill HR-3636 National Communications
<br> Competition and Information Infrastructure
<br> Act of 1993 Introduced by Reps. Markey, Fields
<br> and Boucher
<br>markey_fields_hr3636_hr3626_ecc-tfs.testimony - Feb 1994 testimony of
<br> Edward Horowitz (CEO of
<br> Viacom) before the house
<br> energy and commerce's
<br> telecommunications and finance
<br> subcommittee relating to
<br> interactive video systems
<br>markey_hr3636.eff - Daniel Weitzner's March 1994 article announcing that Rep.
<br> Markey has Endorsed EFF's Open Platform Proposal
<br> through hr 3636. Briefly, EFF's Open Platform Proposal
<br> suggests policies to make voice, data and video services
<br> accessible to everyone, in the near term, and at low cost.
<br> Without a deliberate effort by government, business and
<br> individuals to build these requirements into the
<br> communications infrastructure, the free speech protections
<br> guaranteed by the Constitution will be in jeopardy
<br>markey_hr3636.statement - March 1994 news release announcing that hr 3636
<br> unanimously passed in the house telecom and finance
<br> subcommittee. It also includes a summary of the
<br> bill and Markey's March 1994 statement regarding
<br> the
<br> Information Infrastructure Act of 1993, &quot; and H.R.
<br> 3626, the &quot;Antitrust Reform Act of 1993.&quot;
<br>markey_hr3636_kapor.testimony - testimony of Mitch Kapor (EFF) before the
<br> subcommittee on telecom and finance regarding
<br> the national communications competition and
<br> information infrastructure act (HR 3636)
<br>markey_hr1305_cnid_91.bill - the TCPR bill of 1991 amending the Communications
<br> Act of 1934 to protect the rights of telephone
<br> subscribers
<br>markey_telecom_draft_91_kapor.testimony - Testimony of Mitch Kapor of the EFF
<br> before the subcommittee on telecom
<br> and finance regarding telecom
<br> infrastructure legislation and
<br> proposals In October 1991
<br>moran_hr3365.bill - House of Reps &quot;Drivers Privacy Protection Act of 1993&quot;
<br>rose_s564.bill - 
<br>simon_s984.bill - The &quot;Privacy for Consumers and Workers Act of 1993&quot; to
<br> prevent abuses of electronic monitoring in the workplace,
<br> and for other purposes introduced by Simon
<br>valentine_encrypt_stds_bill.draft - july 1994 staff discussion draft
<br> of legislation to authorize the
<br> Administration to develop and issue,
<br> by regulation, federal encryption
<br> standards for ensuring the privacy,
<br> security, and authenticity of domestic and
<br> international electronic communications
<br> in a way that preserves privacy rights and
<br> maintains the government's authority and
<br> ability to conduct electronic surveillance
<br>
</H5>



