<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="CPC"><B>CPC</B></a>
<DD>Directory of information relating to NPTN's plans for a Corporation for
    Public Cybercasting.
<DT><a href="about.nptn"><B>about.nptn</B></a>
<DD>background information concerning the Community Computing and
    the National Public Telecomputing Network
<DT><a href="affiliate.list"><B>affiliate.list</B></a>
<DD>August 1993 list of affiliate systems and organizing
    committees related to the national public telecomputing
    network.
<DT><a href="by_state.list"><B>by_state.list</B></a>
<DD>July 1994 updated list of affiliate systems and organizing
    committees related to the national public telecomputing
    network
<DT><a href="dangers_to_comnets.article"><B>dangers_to_comnets.article</B></a>
<DD>Jan. 1996 article by Doug Schuler of the 
    Seattle Community Network, on several things that can kill community 
    networking efforts.
<DT><a href="educational_affiliates.list"><B>educational_affiliates.list</B></a>
<DD>c.1993 list of educational affiliates.
<DT><a href="login.info"><B>login.info</B></a>
<DD>October 1993 login information for community computer systems.
<DT><a href="nptn_closes.announce"><B>nptn_closes.announce</B></a>
<DD>Sad announcement of the bankruptcy and closure of 
    NPTN, Sept. 1996.
<DT><a href="rural.outreach"><B>rural.outreach</B></a>
<DD>Article discussing that the development of NPTN community
    computer systems has, up to this point, primarily been an
    urban phenomena because linking rural locations into the
    major electronic highways is a non-trivial event. 
    However, it adds, NPTN is pleased to announce the receipt
    of a $25,000 grant to develop a Rural Community Computer
    Program
<DT><a href="services.catalog"><B>services.catalog</B></a>
<DD>Fall 1993 catalog of cybercasting services
<DT><a href="setbacks_in_canada.note"><B>setbacks_in_canada.note</B></a>
<DD>discussion of an archaic 1891 tax rule has
    slammed the doors on a major avenue of fundraising
    for Canadian freenets
</DL>

