<h2><A NAME="onsite">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/door_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 
ALT=""></A> Related On-Site Resources</h2>
<DL>
<DT>[no Related On-Site Resources]
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
<h2><A NAME="offsite">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/earth2_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Links to Related Off-Site Resources</h2>
<DL>

<DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/PICS/"><B>Platform for Internet 
Content Selection (PICS)</B></A>
<DD>Originally a proposal of the <A 
HREF="http://home.netscape.com/newsref/pr/newsrelease29.html">Information 
Highway Parental Empowerment Group (IHPEG)</A>, a consortium of Netscape, 
Microsoft, and Progressive Networks. PICS today is a project of a broader 
organization, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
The PICS standard is a proposal for Internet content 
labelling systems that allows for multiple labelling systems and other
key features (this proposal is, however, under some attack as misguided.
See the SAFE site below.) PICS has some rather unique features, including
it's adaptability to other issues than content filtering, such as privacy 
protection. PICS-based systems have already been released as of late 1996.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.netshepherd.com">Net Shepherd's daxHOUND"</A></B>
<DD>A PICS-based labelling system in which Net participants rather than
a ratings team do the ratings. Intended to be a more democratic system
of Net filtration than the more usual model.
<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.aaa.com.au/matilda">Matilda</A></B>
<DD>Beta test the first public PICS-based WWW search engine (now running
a SafeSurf engine).

<DT><A HREF="http://www.xmission.com/~seer/jdksoftware/"><B>The Internet
    Filter</B></A> site
    <DD>Internet Filter is a free software tool for parents to
    use in filtering net material for their children, or for individuals to
    use for filtering what they themselves receive. I.F. simply blocks 
receipt or transmission of "objectionable" words and phrases. This is a 
crude approach that blocks a wide range of non-sexual material.  I.F.
uses neither a "blacklist", nor PICS, only keyword searching.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.planetview.com">PlanetView</A></B>
<DD>This is a rather sad story.  PlanetView (originally NewView) launched 
a rather crude "whitelist"-based filter, called iScreen (only sites on the 
whitelist were accessible). Realizing this wouldn't fly, NewView came up 
with a really interesting project called Specs for Kids, which combined 
sophisticated filtering with the most-customizable filtration criteria of 
any such system, behind which was a PICS-like ratings system. iScreen was 
retained as a kind a Yahoo for kids, turing it into a positive rather 
than negative tool.  Then the monetary bottom fell out.  The only thing 
left of all of this is the rating system and some filters for it, and it 
only works on the Sega Saturn NetLink's PlanetWeb browser. It would appear 
that  NewView went belly up, saved only by a contract with Sega, for whom 
they are now an exclusive.  At any rate, if Sega is your platform, <A 
HREF="http://view.planetweb.com/cust/ss_lvl1.html">PlanetView's Parental 
Controls</A> would appear to be the only game going.  

<DT><B>Solid Oak Software's <A 
HREF="http://www.solidoak.com/cysitter.htm">CYBERsitter</A>
    and <A HREF="http://www.solidoak.com/vcr.htm">Voluntary
 Content Rating System</A></B>
    <DD>CYBERsitter is another Windows-based net filtration tool.  As of
    mid-1996, it was one of the more censorious, barring access to numerous
    political and social sites, newsgroups, etc., including the National
    Organization for Women, and other online content that has nothing to
    do with pornography.  According to CyberWire Dispatch, CYBERsitter is
    the preferred net.filter for the theocratic organization Focus on the 
    Family.  The VCR System is a one-line Web page rating code system,
    intended to be simpler and easier to use than PICS, and intending only
    that "adult" pages be rated ("Why should those publishing totally 
    innocent web pages have to comply with a rating system standard 
    because of a relative few adult web site publishers?")  Mixed messages?
    As of Dec. 1996, Solid Oak was blocking access to CYBERsitter critics,
    and threatening to block access to *all* customers of any ISP hosting
    a critic's web pages.  In this case at least, the "cure" of filtration
    would seem as bad as or worse than the "disease" of government 
    censorship.

<DT><A HREF="http://www.surfwatch.com/"><B>Surfwatch</B></A> site
    <DD>Surfwatch is yet another net-filtration tool, primarily aimed at
    parents. Surfwatch is based on a "blacklist" model, and will block
    material you probably didn't expect it to, because of the subjective
    system used by Surfwatch's ratings team. Comparative tests by C|Net 
    found that it did not block some sites it probably should have.

<DT><A HREF="http://www.netnanny.com/netnanny/home.html"><B>NetNanny</B></A>
    <DD>another net.filter, based on simple but arguably effective 
techniques like cutting the
    connection if any word from a list of "forbidden" words appears on the
    screen.  Appears to have some major bugs, as CyberWire Dispatch reports
    that as of July 1996, NetNanny prohibits access to numerous technical
    forums, including such things as the computer-architecture mailing list
    at cs.colorado.edu.  Has a particularly interesting feature of preventing
    your child from transmitting your address, phone number, or credit 
    card number over the Internet. Has other local-machine protection 
    features, like disabling of hard-drive formatting.  One very serious 
privacy concern, despite the credit card and address blocking, is that 
NetNanny creates an "audit trail", viewable by parents, of where a child 
has been browsing.  Such a "feature" though it may sound good to nosy 
parents, could actually prove disastrous. Imagine what could happen, for 
example, after a child's abusive parents learn she has been visiting or 
attempting to visit sites dealing with teen pregnancy, gay youth support 
groups, or child abuse. Unlike some other services, 
NetNanny operates without  the child knowing it is there.  Besides being 
spy-like, this could have other negative consequences (i.e. large phone 
bills when Junior calls Microsoft tech support several times in an 
attempt to figure out why the computer keeps shutting down.) 

<DT><B><A HREF="http://wex.www.media.mit.edu/people/wex/rate-proposal.html">
    Automated Collaborative Filtering (ACF)</A></B>
    <DD>A Community-Based Ratings Alternative for the Net

<DT><B><A HREF="http://homr.www.media.mit.edu/projects/homr">HOMR</A></B>
<DD>An ACF-based online content ratings system.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.vtw.org/ipcfaq">Voters Telecommunications 
Watch's Frequently Asked Questions and Answers About Internet Parental 
Control Technology</A></B>

<DT><B><A 
HREF="http://webhound.www.media.mit.edu/projects/webhound">WebHound</A></B>
<DD>An ACF-based online content ratings system

<DT><B><A 
HREF="http://www.organic.com/Staff/brian/community-filters.html">Community Filters</A></B>
<DD>A predecessor of ACF.

<DT><A HREF="http://www.cyberpatrol.com/">Cyber Patrol & Cyber Sentry</A>
<DD>Another scheme for "protecting children from the net".  The
    advertising here is really a bit much, harping on the "dangerous" 
    Internet. At any rate, as of mid-1996, Cyber Patrol blocks
    access to numerous political and social sites and groups, including
    soc.support.fat-acceptance, soc.feminism, clari.news.women, parts of
    of EFF's own archives, sites having to do with the Second Amendment to
    the US Constitution, the League for Programming Freedom, Queer Resources
    Directory, EnviroLink, and drug-related material.  CyberPatrol is built
    into both Compuserve and Prodigy, and also available in a stand-alone
    version (called NetBlocker Plus).

<DT><A 
HREF="http://www.mit.edu:8001/activities/safe/safe/labeling/summary.html">
<B>SAFE's Rating &amp; Labelling Schemes info pages</B></A>
<DD>From the 1954 Comics Code to 1995's PICS Internet labelling proposal

<DT><A 
HREF="http://www.clickshare.com/clickshare/usrintro.html"><B>Clickshare</B></A>
<DD>system to allow users to block content, without imposing a ratings
system on e-publishers. Also (even primarily) geared to facilitate online 
commerce by handling microtransactions, etc.

<DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/pub/Conferences/WWW4/Papers/117/"><B>Bell 
Labs/Lucent Technology's Signet prototype rating/filtering service via 
WWW proxy</B></A>

<DT><A HREF="http://www.mckinley.com/mckinley-txt/250.html#greenlight"><B>
McKinley Group's "Magellan" Internet index/search service</B></A>
<DD>supports a 
"green light" system of content labelling for "kid-safe" materials. Unlike
most proposed solutions to the perceived child access problem, Magellan
provides positive pointers instead of negative blocking, and leaves it to
parents to instruct their children how to behave online.

<DT><A HREF="http://www.cais.net/cannon/memos/parents.htm"><B>A Parent's 
Guide to Supervising a Child's Online and Internet Experience</A></B>
<DD>"A short guide to how the Internet works and what parents can do to 
guide their childrens' online experiences." By Robert Cannon of the 
Washington, D.C. law firm Shack, Crawford & Cannon

<DT><B><A HREF="http://yellodyno.safe-t-child.com/index.html">
SAFE-T-CHILD ONLINE</A></B>
<DD>"ENTERTAINMENT-DRIVEN CHILD SAFETY!" (mostly offline safety issues, 
but also has a feature on protecting children from online pedophiles,
if any more of them are left after the FBI roundup.)

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.n2h2.com/">N2H2 Internet Filters</A>
<DD>"N2H2 is committed to making the Internet a more accessible resource 
for schools, businesses and families", and provides server resident 
filtration systems for corporations and schools, as well as for home use.
Their main line of work is in providing pre-filtered Net access (i.e., 
they server as an ISP, and route all web browsing through their in-house 
filtration system.  N2H2, like most services, uses a "blacklist" method 
of filtering.  But they also provide for "whitelisting", and have 
demonstrated this capability with their <A 
HREF="http://www.bess.net">BESS</A>
site for kids. (The above link is to me BESS demo itself. Click <A 
HREF="http://www.n2h2.com/schools/">here</A> for more info about BESS
and how it works.)


<DT><B><A HREF="http://nix.ha.md.us/~caro/agecheck.html">AgeCheck</A></B>
<DD>An age-verification system for online users & services. Useful for 
ruling out minors' accessing sexually-explicit material, for commercial 
sites. As with all such systems, including credit card verification, not
much of a solution for individual or non-profit content providers.

<DT><B>Yahoo! &amp; SurfWatch present <A 
HREF="http://www.yahooligans.com/docs/safety">
&quot;Staying Street Smart on the Web!&quot;, and &quot;Rules for Online 
Child Safety&quot;</A></B>
<DD>Part of the Yahoo/SurfWatch "whitelist" project, <A 
HREF="http://www.yahooligans.com">Yahooligans</A> (a strangely negative 
name for something intended to seem positive).

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.safesurf.com">SafeSurf</A></B> filtration service
<DD>and their <A HREF="http://www.safesurf.com/lifegard.htm">Internet 
Lifeguard</A> tips for "safe" web surfing.  One grows weary of this 
"safety" metaphor-stretching.  SafeSurf is a non-commercial effort, 
essentially a cataloguing service for self-labels. Among the first in the 
field, SafeSurf claims over 50,000 registered "sites", which many mean
machines or may mean web pages. SafeSurf is intended to work with PICS.

<DT><B><A 
HREF="http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/diglib/pub/reports/BRIOTR/">ComMentor</A></B>
<DD>An architecture for group annotations to web pages. Far broader that 
"filtering out bad stuff", but can do that too.  The system can be wedded to
web browser design (info on doing so, and incorporating ACF ratings 
prototypes is available <A 
HREF="http://www.ai.mit.edu/people/lethin/rating.html">here</A>).

<DT><B>Alex Stewart's <A 
HREF="http://www.crl.com/~riche/IVSR/proposal.html">Voluntary
Internet Self Rating (IVSR) proposal</A></B>

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.teachersoft.com">TeacherSoft's "InterGO"</A></B>
<DD>with built-in filtering, <A 
HREF="http://www.teachersoft.com/tour/kguard.htm">KinderGuard</A> 
(PICS-compliant; also uses SafeSurf).
InterGO is essentially a filtering Web browser with other utilities built-in 
(e.g. address book & email), based on a non-technical metaphoric 
interface (you select items, such as a globe or a pencil from a rendered 
desktop).  Most of the parental controls from other companies are add-ons 
for browsers, rather than browsers themselves. InterGO, which appears to 
be based on Mosaic, also references TeacherSoft's own "whitelist" 
collection of rated and kid-approved sites.  An all-around solution, but
building it into a browser limits the user's upgrage path - probably not 
a good idea give how fast the Web is evolving, and the resources browser 
specialists can bring to bear in keeping up.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.algorithm.com/internet/watchdog.html">Internet
WatchDog</A></B>
<DD>An Internet usage monitoring tool (does not do blocking). Keeps logs, 
does periodic screen captures, etc. Aimed at both the child market and 
employee monitoring.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.privnet.com/">Internet Fast Forward</A> by 
PrivNet</B>
<DD>a specialized filter to weed out advertisements in the form of
"banner" graphics, of particular interest to parents concerned about 
e-commercials bombarding their children.  Also does other "feature 
filtering", such blocking out annoying blinking text in web pages, etc.
A version was released in early 1996, no longer available. PrivNet, the 
company that produced it has been bought by PGP. PGP says they do plan 
to put out an updated version, so check the <A 
HREF="http://www.privnet.com">PrivNet</A> and <A 
HREF="http://www.pgp.com">PGP</A> web sites for updates every so often.

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.webster.com">WebTrack</A></B>
<DD>A filter & monitoring system intended to be used by employers to track
(and block, when deemed appropriate) employee web usage.  An example of a 
filtering system gone overboard. Specifically designed as a spying mechanism,
WebTrack is likely to greatly worsen the already dreadful workplace 
privacy situation.  Webtrack components range from "plug-n-play" 
filtering for any Internetted office, to programmers toolkits for building
WebTrack into 3rd party products, to plug-ins for proxies (i.e. so that a 
proxy can do WebTracking for any number of companies).

<DT><B><A 
HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Content/Reviews/Compare/Safesurf/">C|Net 
comparatively reviews the performance of 8 Net filtration "solutions".</A>
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
