alt="------------------------------"></center>
<center><h1>Articles and Critiques</h1></center>

<blockquote>

<img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a href="human.rights.txt">U.S. State Department's "Zambia Human
Rights Practices Report"</a>

<i><br>Police often ignore procedural requirements and engage in abusive and
brutal behavior, including beating and at times killing criminal
suspects and detainees... The press and other media continued to run
afoul of legal restraints on freedom of expression and suffered
political reprisals for expressing independent views.</i>

<p>
<img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a href="http://www.zamnet.zm/zamnet/post/post.html"><i>The Post</i>
newspaper</a>

<blockquote>
<p><a
href="http://www.zamnet.zm/zamnet/post.arch.7440/news/fpstory.html">Article
on arrest and raid</a> (2/7/96)
<br><i>These charges were placed after the Republican President Frederick
Chiluba signed statutory instrument number 33 of 1996 on Monday
declaring The Post edition of Monday a prohibited publication.</i>

<p><a href="http://www.zamnet.zm/zamnet/post.arch.7440/editor/story1.html">
Post editorial on arrest and raid</a> (2/7/96)
<br><i>The government has shown that it is willing to jail people who
will in any way pose as a hinderance to having a Constitution adopted
in a manner and with content that they feel comfortable with.</i>

<p><a
href="http://www.zamnet.zm/zamnet/post.arch.7440/editor/story2.html">President
Frederick Chiluba's
reply</a> (2/7/96)
<br><i>
The Post has been notorious for trying to lower the integrity of the presidency and reduce it to that of
an ordinary citizen, which is quite outrageous.</i>

<p><a
href="http://www.zamnet.zm/zamnet/post.arch.23314/news/story1.html">Statement
on Post web site</a> (2/6/96)

<br><i>Due to a disruption of the production of this edition as a result of a
ten (10) hour night search of The Post editorial office on Cha Cha
Road by the state police, we are unable to complete all our work and
offer full news coverage. By midnight police had in fact ordered us to
stop production. In the meantime our offices have been sealed by
security personnel.</i>

</blockquote>

<img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a href="http://www.zamnet.zm/">Zamnet Communication Systems Ltd.</a>

<p><img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a
href="http://www.sas.upenn.edu/African_Studies/Urgent_Action/misa_zmbia.html">Media Institute of South Africa calls for sanctions on Zambia</a> (12/14/94)

<p><img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a
href="http://www.sas.upenn.edu/African_Studies/Urgent_Action/zmbia_misa.html">MISA
Zambia press alert update</a> (12/13/94)

<p><img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a href="report.102494.txt">Article on press regulation in Zambia</a> (10/24/94)

<p><img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*"> <a
href="http://snipe.ukc.ac.uk/international/papers.dir/chan1.html">Stephen
Chan's essays on Zambian politics and economy</a> (1991)

<p><img src="graphics/dark.red-ball.gif" alt="*">
<a href="ftp://ftp.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/user/declan/ftp/post.020696.txt">Download
the text-only version of the banned issue</a> (2/6/96)

</blockquote>

